06785nam a22010215i 9789048552450DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485524507 a10.1515/97890485524502doi  a(DE-B1597)624047  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aBL1278.54b.P69 2022 7aHEA0250002bisacsh04a294.5/436223/eng/2022090604aThe Power of the Nath Yogis :bYogic Charisma, Political Influence and Social Authority /ced. by Eloisa Stuparich, Daniela Bevilacqua. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion and Society in Asia ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tForeword -- tNote on Transliterations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Current Research on Nāth Yogīs . Further Directions -- t2 Powerful Yogīs . The Successful Quest for Siddhis and Power -- t3 Kingly Corruption and Ascetic Sovereignty in the Telugu Account of the Nine Nāths -- t4 In Siddhis and State . Transformations of Power in Twentieth-Century Gorakhpur Temple Publications -- t5 The Search for the Jugi Caste in Pre-Colonial Bengal -- t6 Back When We Were Brahmins . Historical and Caste Critique Among Bengali Householder Nāths -- t7 Shades of Power . The Nāth Yogīs in Nepal -- t8 Yogī, Paṇḍit, and Rāṣṭra-Bhakta . Some Reconstructions of Yogī Naraharināth’s Religious Career -- t9 The Evocative Partnerships of a Monastic Nāth Temple in Contemporary Rajasthan -- t10 Towards a Nāth Re-Appropriation of Haṭha-Yoga -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe volume collects a series of contributions that help reconstruct the recent history of the N.th tradition, highlighting important moments of self.reinterpretation in the samprad.ya’s interaction with different social milieus. The leitmotif tying together the selection of articles is the authors’ explorations of the overlap between religious authority and political power. For example, in which ways do the N.ths’ hagiographical claim of possessing yogic charisma (often construed as supernatural powers, siddhis) translate into mundane expressions of socio.political power? And how does it morph into the authority to reinterpret and recreate particular traditions? The articles approach different aspects of the recent history of the N.th samprad.ya, spanning from stories of yog.s guiding kings in the petty principalities of the eighteenth century to gurus who sought prominence in the transnational environments of the twentieth century; examining some N.th lineages and institutions under the British Raj, in the history of Nepal, and in contemporary India.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aNātha sect. 4aAsian Studies. 4aContemporary Society. 4aEast Asian religions. 4aIndia. 4aNepal. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aReligion and Theology. 4aReligion and politics. 4aSocial groups: religious groups and communities. 4aSociology and Social History. 4aSouth Asia. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Yoga.2bisacsh  aYogi, Power, Politics, Asceticism.1 aBevilacqua, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBevilacqua, Daniela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBordeaux, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBouillier, Véronique, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHawthorne Higgins, Carter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Jamal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarrewa-Karwoski, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuñoz, Adrián, econtributor.4ctb4https://